items.name: Occult Geometry
items.description:
Introducing Occult Geometry Model: An AI Model for Generating Images of Occultism and Sacred Geometry

Occult Geometry Model is a specialized AI model designed to generate captivating images inspired by the realms of occultism and sacred geometry. Trained on a simple yet carefully curated dataset, and undergoing 20 epochs and 1280 steps, this model possesses the ability to create mesmerizing visual representations that evoke the mysticism and intricate patterns associated with occultism and sacred geometry.

The dataset used to train Occult Geometry Model consists of a selection of images and reference materials that encompass various aspects of occultism and sacred geometry. These include symbols, esoteric motifs, geometric patterns, and other visual elements that are commonly associated with occult practices and the exploration of sacred geometrical principles. Through its exposure to this dataset, Occult Geometry Model has acquired a deep understanding of the visual aesthetics and symbolism inherent in occultism and sacred geometry.

items.name: Rimming Poses
items.description:
Kiss me where it smells funny!

This is a very personal upload with a little background story: some days ago i had a short argument with another civitai user. At the end (s)he told me, that i had made the most pointless and disturbing model on civitai (referring to my Licking Armpit Poses upload). That hurt ... a bit.

So what was the only logical thing to do? Yes, exactly, upload something similarly pointless and disturbing, then at least one of those downloads would definitely not be the most pointless and disturbing anymore. Thus it is an honor for me to present to you: Rimming poses for controlnet's openpose, normal and softedge models. Hf :)

1.0: Wow, standing backwards is a hard thing to do. Well, at least for some checkpoints. Although URPM has been my go to base model for the realistic depiction of sex from the beginning, this made me searching for alternatives (have a look at suggested resources). So, with the right checkpoint consistency is quite bearable.

I added two openpose variants of the pose as the median distance between butt and face seems to differ from checkpoint to checkpoint. Jokes aside, hopefully it gives you another option if a base model decides to not place the face where it should be for successful buttmunching. Usually Balanced and a weight of 1.0-1.5 seems to work best for openpose.

For the other two types it might be neccessary to experiement a bit more with the controlnet settings, usually you can/should decrease the weight quite a bit with them.

As always: best used with 3:2/2:3 resolutions.

2nd part of my CIA - Controlnet Is Awesome collection. To be continued...

items.name: Minori (Deathblight) Crescentia Fortuna's Character LoRA
items.description:
Crescentia's character from the Deathblight webcomic the Wolf Girl Minori. Works well on 0.6-1.0 though the comic style is more noticeable at higher weights. training done on NAI.

Trigger: "Minori, Wolf girl" always needed, "slit pupils, muscular" for accuracy.

Outfits:

  • Dress: "halterneck, choker, halter dress, purple dress, sash, black thighhighs, elbow gloves, fingerless gloves"

  • Hair options:

  • "black hair, Short hair, messy hair"

  • "black hair, Long hair, messy hair"

"Fingerless gloves" are part of the dress outfit but always have a hard time generating normal fingers but using a pose "Hands on hips", "waving" help achieve better results.

Do not prompt an Eye colour as Minori has very particular eyes that are well trained in. I highly recommend the ADetailer extension in A1111 for the face and is helps a lot at cleaning up the eyes but it is not needed for more close-up shots.

My personal favorite character from the Deathblight comic and is the best buddy of Ferania. She gave me a battle with the trainer to figure out why "criss-cross halter" is a bad tag and "halterneck" is loads better. I hope you all enjoy.

Feedback and reviews are always appreciated.

items.name: Norman Bates (Psycho 2 / 3 / 4) Lora
items.description:
This model is made from pictures of Anthony Perkins as Norman Bates in the later Psycho sequels since the original is entirely black and white and I'm still figuring out how to do those. OG Norman will happen though.

Be nice, have fun!

Norman Bates is a fictional character created by American author Robert Bloch as the main antagonist in his 1959 thriller novel Psycho. He has an alter, Mother, who takes from the form of his abusive mother, and later victim, Norma, who in his daily life runs the Bates Motel.

He was portrayed by Anthony Perkins in the 1960 version of Psycho directed by Alfred Hitchcock and in the Psycho franchise. He was also portrayed by Vince Vaughn in the 1998 version of Psycho, and by Freddie Highmore in the television series Bates Motel (20132017).[1]

Unlike the franchise produced by Universal Studios, Norman is not the principal antagonist in Bloch's subsequent novels and is succeeded by copycat killers who assume Norman's identity after his death in Psycho II (1982), although he does return in the licensed continuation novel Psycho: Sanitarium (2016) by Chet Williamson, and the comic book series Son of Psycho (2021). There is a wide-ranging assumption that the character was directly inspired by the Wisconsin murderer Ed Gein. With Psycho being optioned for film adaptation as a direct result of media attention on Gein, Bloch later revealed he was inspired more by the circumstances surrounding Gein's casethe idea that "the man next door may be a monster unsuspected even in the gossip-ridden microcosm of small-town life." Years later, when the full details of Gein's crimes were revealed, he was struck by "how closely the imaginary character I'd created resembled the real Ed Gein both in overt act and apparent motivation."[2]

items.name: Epeulu Style
items.description:
Makes images in a monochrome/greyscale style with hatching textures.

How to use
While the dataset was very small this style LoRA came out rather versatile so you should be able to prompt most things. Approx half of the images had Chainsaw Man content so anything from that should work particularly well. For more tips see the sample images and uploaded zip of tags.

Recommended strength is anything from 0.5 to 1.0 depending on what you prompt. The non-human stuff requiring higher values. For samples I recommend DIMM or DPM++ 2M Karras since those best recreate the hand drawn style.

MISC
Trained on NAI at 512px with a dataset of 25 images.
All images are raw txt2img upscaled without any inpainting or helper embeddings.
The training was done on a small subset of the artists images, as such the output of this LoRA is not an accurate representation neither in quality or style of the artist Epeulu. Go support them if you want the good stuff.
